AttributeValuesData.AttributeValue: The Striped Maple is a large shrub or small tree named for the white striping on its young green bark. A. pensylvanicum is native to the Northeastern United States and is most typically found in the understory of moist, cool hardwood forests. The Striped Mapel is the largest of the world's group of 21 "snakebark" maples (all with vertical stripes on the bark), and the only one that is not native to China or Japan. It grows biggest in the southern Appalachians. The fruit provides food for small mammals, and the foliage is browsed by moose and deer. Does not grow well in adverse conditions.
Smooth, young stems greenish with long, vertical white stripes. Older trunks loose the pronounced striping
1/2" wide (larger than other maple flowers), pyramidal clusters, yellow, late spring
paired samaras with leaves spreading at a wide angle, 2" hanging in long linear clusters, July-Sept
Opposite, simple, roundish obovate, 3 shallowly divided broad lobes, 5-9" long and wide, hairless on both surfaces, autumn color vivid yellow.
Vertical white striping on young green bark
demands shade and protection from sun, wind
